{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox artwork | title = Children Are the Victims of Adult Vices | image_file = Children Are the Victims of Adult Vices.jpg | caption = | image_size = | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Mihail Chemiakin]] | catalogue = | year = <!-- {{start date|YYYY}} remove date template if before 1583 CE --> | completion_date = 2001 (unveiled)<!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} - for more specific dates --> | type = [[Bronze sculpture]] | material = | subject = | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. --> | imperial_unit = in<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default in. --> | condition = | city = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] | coordinates = {{coord|55.745935|37.619376|type:landmark|display=inline;title}}<!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} - Only use for the exact coordinates of the artwork itself (and only where known) and not for the coordinates of the museum. Leave blank if coordinates are not known. --> | owner = | url = <!--{{URL|example.com}} Only for official web pages--> }} '''''Children Are the Victims of Adult Vices''''' is a group of [[bronze sculpture]]s created by [[Russian people|Russian]] artist [[Mihail Chemiakin]]. The sculptures are located in a park in [[Bolotnaya Square]], [[Balchug]], {{convert|2000|ft|abbr=off}} south of the [[Moscow Kremlin]] behind the [[British Ambassador to Russia|British Ambassador's]] residence.<ref>{{cite news| author = Yablokova, Oksana | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-45469973.html |title=Moscow to Raise Monument to People's Sins |date=29 June 2001| publisher = ''[[The Moscow Times]]'' (via [[Highbeam Research]]) |accessdate= 12 January 2015}}</ref>
The sculptures are of thirteen figures, which depict adult [[vice]]s, such as alcoholism, drug addiction, and prostitution, that affect children.<ref name="BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/monitoring/media_reports/1426475.stm|title=Moscow divided over vices statue|date=6 July 2001| publisher = [[BBC News]] |accessdate=26 December 2008}}</ref> The figures are perceptibly closing in on two unaware playmates, a girl and a boy, with the centrepiece figure being 'Indifference'.
The sculpture was commissioned by then-Mayor [[Yuri Luzhkov]] and sponsored by the state-owned oil company [[Rosneft]]. It was unveiled in 2001 amid some controversy. Some Muscovites worried that the graphic imagery would frighten children.<ref name="BBC" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pravoslavie.ru/guest/abramenkova.htm|title="ПАМЯТНИК ПОРОКАМ" ШЕМЯКИНА С ТОЧКИ ЗРЕНИЯ ПСИХОЛОГА (an interview with doctor of psychological sciences Vasilevnoy Abramenkovoy)| last=Shishova| first=Tatiana|date=5 December 2001|publisher=www.pravoslavie.ru|language=Russian|accessdate= 26 December 2008}}</ref> Chemiakin said that, "[The sculpture] ... was conceived and carried out by me as a symbol and a call to fight for the salvation of present and future generations."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.log-in.ru/articles/560/|title=The children – victims of adult vices|last=Darina|first=Nikonov|publisher=www.log-in.ru|language=Russian|accessdate= 26 December 2008}}</ref>
